## Arabic Quranic stratum: Adam, Barzakh, jinn, Iblis's counter-signal

**Q2 (composite Adam).** Q 2:30-34 calls Adam *khalīfa* (خليفة), explicitly **does NOT** say later souls are fragments of him. Ṭabarī's preferred reading: Adam succeeds either God's governance or prior jinn-inhabitants; ifsād/dimāʾ is committed by *dhurriyya* (descendants), syntactically independent of Adam. The closest text to "Adam contained all souls" is Q 7:172's *dharr* episode (mass extraction of soul-points from Adam's back/loins) — but the dharr are presented as *separate persons*, not as parts of one composite nafs. Ibn ʿArabī's *Fass Ādamī* presents Adam as *al-insān al-kāmil* (the cosmic mirror) — a structural-jami collective, NOT a mechanical-shrapnel composite. **The "all humans are shards of Adam's broken soul" framing is a modern simplification** not warranted by the classical tafsīr. Confidence high.

**Q3 (Barzakh).** Ṭabarī's preferred gloss on Q 23:100 is *ḥājiz yaḥjuz baynahum wa-bayna al-rujūʿ* — "a barrier preventing return." The directionality matters: the Barzakh blocks **the dead from returning**, not external entities from entering. Munkar/Nakīr, ḥayyāt (serpents), and ʿaqārib (scorpions) all *enter* the qabr per the standard ḥadīth corpus quoted by Ibn Kathīr. **No classical text describes Barzakh as "secure" against external access.** This contradicts modern apologetic summaries. Confidence high.

**Q4 (Iblis's counter-cry).** Documented in Biḥār al-Anwār vol. 52 and Nuʿmānī's *Ghayba* with two attested variants: «ألا إن الحق في عثمان وشيعته» and «ألا إن الحق في السفياني وشيعته» — **structurally mimicking** the true cry «ألا إن الحق في علي/المهدي وشيعته». Distinguishing criteria are explicit: (a) **time/place** — true cry from the sky at dawn, false from earth/air at dusk; (b) **content** — names ʿAlī/the Qāʾim vs. ʿUthmān/Sufyānī; (c) **prior knowledge** — Imām al-Ṣādiq states: «يعرفها من كان سمع بها قبل أن تكون» ("only one who has heard of it beforehand recognizes it"). Kāmil al-Dīn and al-Kāfī mention the Ṣayḥa among the *ʿalāmāt maḥtūmāt* but contain less verbatim detail than Nuʿmānī/Majlisī. Confidence high.

**Q11 (jinn pre-history).** Al-Shiblī (*Ākām al-Marjān*), Ṭabarī, and Ibn Kathīr (*Bidāyah*) consistently transmit: jinn created **2,000 years before Adam** (ʿAbdallāh b. ʿAmr), inhabited and "cultivated" (ʿimāra) Earth, fell into corruption and bloodshed, were killed/exiled to "islands of the seas" by an angelic force under Iblīs — who in some traditions was at that point a guardian (*khāzin*) of paradise from a class of angels called "al-jinn." Pre-jinn earth-inhabitants named *al-ḥinn wa-l-binn* (and *al-nasnās*) are mentioned but underdeveloped. The classical Muslim tradition genuinely contains a **prior-civilization-with-war-and-overthrow** narrative; this is well-attested, not fringe. Confidence medium-high (some isnāds weak, as noted by ibn Bāz on Ākām al-Marjān).

