## Tibetan stratum: no imposters, only non-recognition

**Q7 (Bardo Thödol false lights).** Across all 14 days, the structure is binary: **bright/dazzling/painful wisdom-light** (*'od gsal*, འོད་གསལ་) of one Buddha-family vs. **soft/dull/comforting realm-light** (*'od 'jam po*, འོད་འཇམ་པོ་) of one of six samsaric realms. The dull lights are explicitly *bsu lam* — **"inviting paths" created by one's own habitual tendencies** (*bag chags*). The wrathful blood-drinking herukas of days 8-14 are introduced with the formula *they emerge "from within your own brain" (rang gi klad pa'i nang nas)* — peaceful deities in transformed aspect, **not external imposters**. Standard counter-protocol: *ma 'jigs / ma skrag / ma dngangs* ("do not fear, do not be terrified, do not be awed") + *ngo shes* ("recognize!") + *rang snang yin* ("this is your own self-appearance") + refuge. The text's most "imposter-flavored" passage explicitly says deities *appear as* (*shar* — to dawn) Yama through one's own non-recognition — using the "stuffed lion" simile. **The Bardo Thödol's entire soteriological framework is incompatible with hostile imposters**: every threatening apparition is *rang snang* arising from *rig pa*. **The danger is misrecognition of one's own projections, not deception by external entities.** The most counterintuitive point for Western readers: comforting/soft light is the trap (it leads back to rebirth, even into the heavenly realm); painful brilliance is the liberation. Confidence very high — this is a strict and consistent Dzogchen ontology.

