## Sanskrit stratum: nāgas as cosmic uncles, builders as functional equivalents

**Q10 (Nāgas before humans).** Genealogically yes: Kadrū (mother of nāgas) and Aditi (mother of devas) are both Dakṣa's daughters, both wives of Kāśyapa — making **nāgas, devas, and asuras a peer generation, all of which precede Manu Vaivasvata**, founder of the human lineage. The Samudra Manthana with **Vāsuki used as churning rope** (Ādi Parva 16.12: *manthānaṁ mandaraṁ kṛtvā tathā netraṁ ca vāsukim*) is explicitly **pre-human deva-nāga interaction**. Bhāgavata 5.24.31 catalogs the seven Pātāla cities ruled by Vāsuki, Śaṅkha, Takṣaka, etc. — wealthy underground civilizations. **But**: no primary text frames the Nāga-human chronology as *civilization replaced by civilization*; nāgas coexist with humans throughout cosmic time as a parallel species. The "Nāga civilization preceded human civilization in linear time" claim of ancient-aliens framings overreads the texts. Confidence high.

**Q21 (Maya Dānava).** Sabhā Parva 46 documents the Pāṇḍava sabhā's deliberate *sthala/jala* illusion humiliating Duryodhana — Maya's **architectural māyā** is textually explicit. Śiva Purāṇa Rudra-saṃhitā 2.5.1.55-58: Brahmā commissions Maya to build Tripura's three cities of gold, silver, and iron for Tārakākṣa, Kamalākṣa, and Vidyunmālī. Sūrya Siddhānta 1.2 *itself* names Maya as recipient of solar-planetary knowledge at the end of Satya-yuga. **Critical null-result:** Mahābhārata Karṇa Parva calls the three cities ***puras* (fortified cities), not *vimānas*** — vimānas appear *inside* Tripura as the vehicles of inhabitants, but Maya is nowhere called a vimāna-builder. The "Maya = flying-city engineer = vimāna designer" conflation is modern. **A second null-result:** no primary text explicitly equates Maya-the-builder with māyā-the-cosmic-illusion as doctrine; the pun is poetic, not philosophical. Confidence high on attributions; null on vimāna and māyā-doctrine identifications.

**Q22 (Viśvakarmā vs. Maya).** They never meet face-to-face in any primary text. The Ṛgvedic Viśvakarmā (RV 10.81-82) is a cosmic creator-deity, not yet an artisan (that role belonged to Tvaṣṭṛ). In epic and Purāṇic literature they occupy **parallel niches**: Viśvakarmā = देवशिल्पी (deva-architect: Indra's palace, Lankā, Dvārakā, Indraprastha city); Maya = आसुरशिल्पी (asura-architect: the Pāṇḍava *sabhā* inside Indraprastha, Tripura, Sūrya Siddhānta). **They collaborate** rather than compete in Indraprastha. The closest rivalry: when Maya builds Tripura, **Viśvakarmā builds Śiva's destroying chariot**. **The strongest equation** is Kathāsaritsāgara 34 (Somadeva, c. 1070 CE), which calls Maya **विश्वकर्मणोऽवतारः — "an avatāra of Viśvakarmā"** — the cleanest "two builders, same being" statement in Sanskrit literature, but post-epic kāvya, not Vedic or epic. Also striking: in Śiva Purāṇa 2.5.1.46, **Tārakākṣa's first request is for Viśvakarmā** to build the cities; Brahmā substitutes Maya. The textual implication is functional equivalence. Confidence high.

**Q13 (Pratyabhijñā ↔ Gnostic gnosis).** The structural form is genuinely isomorphic: both treat ignorance as productive (world-generating, not mere absence), both make recognition (not works/faith/sacrifice) the operative soteriological act, both reject acquisition-of-new-content in favor of awakening-to-the-always-given. Utpaladeva's "forgotten-lover" simile (ĪPK IV.1.15) — *kānto loka-samāna evam aparijñāto* — and Kṣemarāja's PHṛ sūtra 12 — *tad-aparijñāne sva-śaktibhir vyāmohitatā saṃsāritvam* — match the Gospel of Truth's "ignorance of the Father brought anguish; when he is known the deficiency vanishes" in deep formal pattern. **But the metaphysical content breaks decisively.** Pratyabhijñā's contraction is *Śiva's own freedom* (*svātantrya*) producing *āṇavamala* as a willed self-veiling — *anugraha-rūpaṃ tirodhānam*, "concealment which is itself a form of grace" (Tantrāloka 1.332). There is **no demiurge, no Yaldabaoth, no archon, no alien power**. The mask is self-imposed by play (*krīḍā*); the cosmos is *pūrṇa-svarūpa-prakāśa* — shining as fullness itself — not a prison. Valentinianism preserves the Father's transcendence by accepting cosmic deficiency; Pratyabhijñā preserves immanent-transcendent fullness by absorbing contraction into Śiva's *svātantrya*. **The two cannot be flattened without distorting one tradition.** The accurate comparative claim: both are **anamnetic non-dual(ish) soteriologies** — the strongest formal parallel in world religion — but Pratyabhijñā is monism-of-self-veiling-as-play; Valentinianism is (attenuated) dualism of self-exile-as-loss. Confidence high.

